TEXT.0: The Electron, Proton, and Alpha Monitor (EPAM) is composed of five

TEXT.1: telescope apertures of three different types.  Two Low Energy

TEXT.2: Foil Spectrometers (LEFS) measure the flux and direction of electrons

TEXT.3: above 30 keV (geometry factor = 0.397 cm2*sr), two Low Energy Magnetic

TEXT.4: Spectrometers (LEMS) measure the flux  and direction of ions greater than 50 keV

TEXT.5: (geometry factor = 0.48 cm2*sr), and the Composition Aperture (CA)

TEXT.6: measures the elemental composition of the ions (geometry factor = 0.24

TEXT.7: cm2*sr). The telescopes use the spin of the spacecraft to sweep the full

TEXT.8: sky. Solid-state detectors are used to measure the energy and composition

TEXT.10: For more information about the EPAM instrument, visit the EPAM Home Page

TEXT.12: The quality of ACE level 2 data is such that it is suitable for serious

TEXT.13: scientific study.  However, to avoid confusion and misunderstanding, it

TEXT.14: is recommended that users consult with the appropriate ACE team members

TEXT.15: before publishing work derived from the data. The ACE team has worked

TEXT.16: hard to ensure that the level 2 data are free from errors, but the team

TEXT.17: cannot accept responsibility for erroneous data, or for misunderstandings

TEXT.18: about how the data may be used. This is especially true if the appropriate

TEXT.19: ACE team members are not consulted before publication. At the very

TEXT.20: least, preprints should be forwarded to the ACE team before publication.
